Problem 2: The Framingham Risk Score¶

In [1]:
# Tip: np.log works element-wise on an np.array

This will be my answer to Question 2: The Framingham Risk Score Here I will show what the system of linear equations to solve for a, b, c, and d are

In [4]:
def conversion(p):
    return np.log(np.log(1-p) / np.log(.95)) + 25.66
risk = np.array([0.1550, 0.1108, 0.0940, 0.0105])
converted_risk = conversion(risk)

age = np.log(np.array([66, 61, 60, 23]))
cholesterol = np.log(np.array([198, 180, 180, 132]))
HDL = np.log(np.array([55, 47, 50, 45]))
SBP = np.log(np.array([132, 124, 120, 132]))

string = "{0:.3f}a + {1:.3f}b + {2:.3f}c + {3:.3f}d = {4:.3f}"
for i in range(0, 4):
    to_print = string.format(age[i],cholesterol[i], 
                             HDL[i],SBP[i],converted_risk[i])
    print(to_print)
    

4.190a + 5.288b + 4.007c + 4.883d = 26.849
4.111a + 5.193b + 3.850c + 4.820d = 26.488
4.094a + 5.193b + 3.912c + 4.787d = 26.315
3.135a + 4.883b + 3.807c + 4.883d = 24.079

Now, I will solve for our unknowns using Python3 code and NumPy

In [5]:
def ind(i):
    return age[i], cholesterol[i], HDL[i], SBP[i]
matrix = np.array([ind(0), 
                   ind(1), 
                   ind(2), 
                   ind(3)])
np.linalg.solve(matrix, converted_risk)

In [9]:
rate1,corrupt1 = scipy.io.wavfile.read('m1.wav')
rate2,corrupt2 = scipy.io.wavfile.read('m2.wav')

Enter the gains to combine the two recordings to get the clean speech.

Note: The square root of a number $a$ can be obtained as np.sqrt(a) in IPython.

In [10]:
# enter the gains u to weight recording 1 and v to weight recording 2
u = np.sqrt(2) / (np.sqrt(3) + 1)
v = np.sqrt(6) / (np.sqrt(3) + 1)

Weighted combination of the two recordings

In [11]:
s1 = u*corrupt1 + v*corrupt2
